<parts xmlns="http://www.sdl.com/xpp"><part.main fileName="1-CHAL_7.DIVXML_0002"><publication online.royalty.id="CALA" uuid="I0f72523026a511d99b08a92d7e97623c"><publication.body><chapter uuid="I49dd324026a611d99b08a92d7e97623c" date.revised="0" date.updated="0"><chapter.body date.updated="0"><analytical.hierarchy uuid="I49df7c3026a611d99b08a92d7e97623c" date.revised="0" date.updated="0"><XPPHier uuid="I49df7c3026a611d99b08a92d7e97623c" name="I. Introduction" parent_uuid="I49dd324026a611d99b08a92d7e97623c">I. Introduction</XPPHier><front date.updated="0"><outline.name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0"><designator date.updated="0"><t style="designator.3">I</t><t style="designator.3 cgt">.</t></designator><name date.updated="0"><t style="name.4">Introduction</t></name></outline.name.block></front><analytical.hierarchy.body date.updated="0"><section.block><section uuid="I49e03f8026a611d99b08a92d7e97623c" date.revised="0" date.updated="0"><XPPMetaData uuid="I49e03f8026a611d99b08a92d7e97623c" guid="I445a1ac6c61c11d9962fb5f8354828db" md.uuid="I445a1ac6c61c11d9962fb5f8354828db" md.dmsserial="303448441" md.first_line_cite="CALRO S 7:1" md.second_line_cite="2 Children &amp;amp; the Law: Rights and Obligations s 7:1" md.pubpage="s 7:1" md.pubid="177882" md.doc_family_uuid="Ie0b81373f8fb11d99f28ffa0ae8c2575" md.normalizedcite="CALROS7:1" md.third_line_cite="" name="&amp;sect; 7:1. Scope of chapter" parent_uuid="I49df7c3026a611d99b08a92d7e97623c">&amp;#167;  7:1. Scope of chapter</XPPMetaData><XPPHier uuid="I49e03f8026a611d99b08a92d7e97623c" name="&amp;sect; 7:1. Scope of chapter" parent_uuid="I49df7c3026a611d99b08a92d7e97623c">&amp;#167;  7:1. Scope of chapter</XPPHier><section.front date.updated="0"><outline.name.block toc.include="y" date.updated="0"><label date.updated="0"><t style="label.2 cgt">§ </t></label><designator date.updated="0"><t style="designator.4">7:1</t></designator><name date.updated="0"><t style="name.5 cgt"> </t><t style="name.5">Scope of chapter</t></name></outline.name.block></section.front><section.body date.updated="0"><para date.updated="0" first.para="yes"><para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes"><t style="para.text">The purpose of this chapter is to familiarize the reader </t><t style="para.text">with guardianship through a summary of guardianship law. </t><t style="para.text">Since guardianship is statutory, there is no substitute for a </t><t style="para.text">review of applicable state law. However, statutes are not </t><t style="para.text">always grouped together in one section or volume and por-</t><t style="para.text">tions of the law may be left to local rules or customs. An </t><t style="para.text">overview of the general law will assist in understanding </t><t style="para.text">guardianship procedures and requirements.</t></para.text></para><para date.updated="0" first.para="no"><para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes"><t style="para.text">A national review of guardianship cannot provide answers </t><t style="para.text">to specific disputed issues among parties in one state, nor </t><t style="para.text">can it cover every possible issue that might be litigated. This </t><t style="para.text">discussion provides the juvenile and family law practitioner </t><t style="para.text">with a basic understanding in order that the statutes of his </t><t style="para.text">or her state can be read more meaningfully and with an </t><t style="para.text">awareness of common issues.</t></para.text></para><para date.updated="0" first.para="no"><para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes"><t style="para.text">Cases presented involve minors, even though adult </t><t style="para.text">incompetency guardianship cases might be applicable. Ap-</t><t style="para.text">pellate review is confined to issues of appointment, removal </t><t style="para.text">of guardian and settlements on account.</t><t style="para.text.1 super cgt">1</t><xref id="2" type="footnote"/><t style="para.text"> Although juries </t><t style="para.text">may be used to hear and determine whether the appoint-</t><t style="para.text">ment of a guardian is necessary, it is the court that decides </t><t style="para.text">who will be appointed as guardian. </t><t style="para.text cgt">‘‘</t><t style="para.text">Notice</t><t style="para.text cgt">’’</t><t style="para.text"> is discussed in </t><pagebreak num="4" num-string="4"/><t style="para.text">relation to the petition process,</t><t style="para.text.1 super cgt">2</t><xref id="3" type="footnote"/><t style="para.text"> although notice regarding </t><t style="para.text">other aspects of guardianship (i.e., notice to creditors), has </t><t style="para.text">been one of the most violated rules in guardianship.</t><t style="para.text.1 super cgt">3</t><xref id="4" type="footnote"/></para.text></para><para date.updated="0" first.para="no"><para.text date.updated="0" first.para.text="yes"><t style="para.text">Some alternatives to guardianship are discussed,</t><t style="para.text.1 super cgt">4</t><xref id="5" type="footnote"/><t style="para.text"> as </t><t style="para.text">counsel may recommend such a course of action in a particu-</t><t style="para.text">lar case. Related issues are addressed in other chapters on </t><t style="para.text">adoption, divorce and mental health.</t><t style="para.text.1 super cgt">5</t><xref id="6" type="footnote"/><t style="para.text"> Forms at the end of </t><t style="para.text">the chapter were collected from various state statutes as a </t><t style="para.text">guide, and may need to be altered for individual use.</t></para.text></para></section.body></section><section uuid="I4a6f120026a611d99b08a92d7e97623c" date.revised="0" date.updated="0"><XPPMetaData uuid="I4a6f120026a611d99b08a92d7e97623c" guid="I445a1ac9c61c11d9962fb5f8354828db" md.uuid="I445a1ac9c61c11d9962fb5f8354828db" md.dmsserial="303448442" md.first_line_cite="CALRO S 7:2" md.second_line_cite="2 Children &amp;amp; the Law: Rights and Obligations s 7:2"